post_text:
Hello 6th Grade Parents!

It saddens me to have to send this email because I look forward to 6th grade orientation every year. Unfortunately due to current circumstances with COVID-19, an in-person orientation was not an effective, safe way to handle this process. So, linked https://youtu.be/q0qhuvZJYwg you will find a video that shows parts of the school, introduces 6th grade teachers, and covers some general information. A video isn't the same, but I hope this helps students learn a little bit of information that they would have learned from orientation night.

If you have any questions, don't hesitate to reach out and I'll help however I can.

Go Pirates!

Adam Hinrichsen | Dean of Students
Alburnett Community Schools
(P): 319-842-2266
(W): www.alburnettcsd.org (E): ahinrichsen@alburnettcsd.org
(A): 131 Roosevelt St. Alburnett, IA 52202
https://youtu.be/q0qhuvZJYwg

Denise Mendenhall-Rawson shared a post to the group: Alburnett's Family & Friends.
July 15 at 12:33 PM ¬∑

If your child qualified for free or reduced meals as of March 16, 2020, please watch for this in the mail. https://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=10159247583508836&id=541763835

Iowa Department of Human Services
July 11 at 5:46 PM ¬∑

Watch your mail for this card!

Pandemic food assistance benefits cards are being mailed to 153,431 Iowa children the next two weeks. If your child was enrolled as a Pre-K through grade 12 student in either a public school or, non-public school that participates in the National School Lunch Program and received Free and Reduced Price School Meals as of March 16, 2020, you will receive this card in a white envelope with an Austin, TX return address.

For full program details, including how to activate the card and what it can be used for, please visit our website - https://dhs.iowa.gov/P-EBT

post_text:
The Alburnett Nutrition Department is happy to announce the continuation of Grab & Go meals through June. This is unique in that we were able to acquire Federal USDA funding to continue to purchase goods, pay staff and support the Food Service Program. We would appreciate your continued support of the program through participation. The meal distribution schedule will remain the same, on Mondays and Thursdays from 11 AM-12:30 PM. Please encourage your children, ages 18 and under to continue to enjoy meals provided. Also encourage your neighbors, family and friends to pick up meals. A bounty of fresh fruits and vegetables will continue to be offered with each meal. Thank you for your continued support! Please email Denise Rawson at drawson@alburnettcsd.org with questions. Mark the following dates on your schedule for meal pick-up:
Monday, June 1st

Thursday, June 4th

Monday, June 8th

Thursday, June 11th

Monday, June 15th

Thursday, June 18th

Monday, June 22nd

Thursday, June 25

Monday, June 29th

Alburnett Community School District Foundation
May 20 at 8:21 PM ¬∑

ANNOUNCING OUR WEEK-LONG ONLINE AUCTION! Please visit our website to register for our first ever online auction. Anyone can register to bid -- no cost to register -- and you do not have to be a past Gala attendee to join in. Go to www.alburnettfoundation.com where instructions are clearly given on how to sign up. Note: You must register by credit card to participate -- no checks for this event. Once you have registered, you will be given information on how to dowload the auction app to your smart phone -- and you can monitor your bids all week long! We will start off the auction with a FB LIVE event at 7pm on Sunday, May 24th. Bidding will close the following Sunday, May 31st at 6pm -- at which time we will make some closing comments on FB LIVE as well. Proceeds from the auction will benefit the projects of the Alburnett Foundation -- specifically the Community Relief Fund and the Pillars Scholarship program. Spread the word -- tell your family and friends!

Good Morning Pirate Families!

I just wanted to send a quick reminder about our Alburnett teachers and staff Wave Caravan we will be doing around our communities on Monday, March 30th starting at 2 PM.

We encourage you to come out (at a safe distance) and wave to the Alburnett teachers and staff as they drive through our school district. Feel free to make signs with messages or just wave as we drive by!

Attached you will find the route we will be driving. For those in the country please join us along the route and wave from your vehicle. There are many safe places along the way to park and wave. We will start in Alburnett and for our non district families will end at King of Kings Church.

We hope to see you Monday!

As we continue to monitor and assess the COVID-19 pandemic, the City of Alburnett is constantly reassessing ways that we can assist in taking action to prevent the potential spread of this virus. Accordingly, the Mayor has just issued a proclamation, effective today (March 17th), closing City Hall with limited access, until further notice. The Mayor‚Äôs proclamation also strongly encourages residents and local businesses to cooperate with all state and federal directives relating to this pandemic. If you need assistance, we ask that you call or e-mail. Our staff will use discretion in determining the urgency of your request. We look forward to working together as a community in being socially responsible to do our part in limiting exposure to all populations. Thank you! - City of Alburnett"

Alburnett Parents and Staff:

Just minutes ago, Iowa schools were notified by Governor Reynolds that school closure is now recommended. Alburnett will be closed beginning Monday, March 16. The building will be closed.

This situation is very fluid. We will continue to share information with you as it becomes available to us. Additional announcements about access to the building to retrieve personal items will be made tomorrow.

Staff, you will not report tomorrow. We ask that you monitor your school email account for additional information.

Sincerely,

Dani Trimble

post_text:
If this isn't a great reminder to vote on March 3rd, we don't know what is!
These 2nd graders from Mrs. Watt's and Ms. Goedken's class didn't hesitate to make a change for a day! The classes visited City Hall and met Mayor McClintock last Friday, February 21st. They got to participate in voting on a "Mayor for the day"! Students first nominated candidates beforhand, they then cast their ballot for their Mayor. The elected mayor was Easton Ford! In Easton's first act as mayor he decreed that there would be an extra recess the following Monday!
